'''John Carbutt''' (1832-1905) was the first person to use [[celluloid]] for photographic film.
He was born in [[Sheffield]], England on 2 December 1832. He moved to Chicago in 1853.
Carbutt founded the [[Keystone Dry Plate Works]] in 1879 and was the first to develop sheets of [[celluloid]] coated with [[photographic emulsion]] for making [[celluloid (film)|celluloid film]] in 1888. Carbutt sliced thin plates from a rigid celluloid block, and then coated them with a silver gelatin emulsion to make a Celluloid Dry plate. Around 1890 he made them in a 35&nbsp;mm width for [[William Kennedy Dickson]]'s [[Kinetoscope]], which set the [[35 mm film]] standard for [[motion picture camera]]s and still [[camera]]s. That format is still the dominant format to this day, as the majority of high end [[digital camera]]s use a 35mm sensor and 35mm film is still being used by a significant number of photographers and film makers.<ref name="hic">{{cite web|url=http://www.historiccamera.com/cgi-bin/librarium2/pm.cgi?action=app_display&app=datasheet&app_id=1782&|title=John Carbutt at Historic Camera - History Librarium|date=23 March 2012|accessdate=26 October 2014}}</ref>
