The '''Salt Lick Award''' is an award given to Canadian manufacturers of foods that demonstrate high sodium levels. The name refers to [[salt lick]]s.
== Purpose and History ==
The award is given by the [[Canadian Stroke Network]], the [[Canadian Obesity Network]] and the Advanced Foods and Materials Network. Some of the baby and toddler foods examined by the two groups had no added sodium, while other foods had levels considered excessive.<ref name="CBC News">{{cite web|title=Gerber toddler meal too salty: stroke group|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/health/story/2010/02/02/salt-gerber.html?ref=rss|work=CBCNews Health|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=2 April 2011|date=2 February 2010}}</ref> The Salt Lick Award is part of World Salt Awareness Week.<ref name="He2011">{{cite journal|last=He|first=Feng J.|author2=Katharine H. Jenner |author3=Clare E. Farrand |author4=Graham A. MacGregor |year=2011|title=World Salt Awareness Week|journal=The Journal of Clinical Hypertension|pages=no–no|issn=1524-6175|doi=10.1111/j.1751-7176.2010.00417.x|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1751-7176.2010.00417.x/full|volume=13|issue=3}}</ref>
==Winners==
*2010 - [[Gerber Products Company|Gerber]] Graduates Lil' Entrees (Chicken & Pasta Wheel Pickups)<ref name="CBC News"/><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.marketwire.com/press-release/2010-Canadian-Salt-Lick-Award-Goes-to-Gerber-Graduates-1110513.htm|title=2010 Canadian "Salt Lick Award" Goes to Gerber Graduates|date=Feb 2, 2010|publisher=Marketwire|accessdate=12 February 2010}}</ref> *2009 - Canadian pizza producers<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.obesitynetwork.ca/page.aspx?page=1619&app=182&cat1=457&tp=12&lk=no&menu=37|title=2009 Canadian "Salt Lick Award" goes to the country’s pizza producers |publisher=Canadian Obesity Network|accessdate=12 February 2010}}</ref> *2008 - [[A&W (Canada)|A&W]] (Chubby Junior Kids' Meal)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/health/story/2008/01/29/salt-lick-award.html|title=A&W given award for most salt content in kid's meals|date=January 29, 2008|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=12 February 2010}}</ref>
